    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nIf a buffer has a `buftype`, LSP won't attach to it without manually calling `vim.lsp.start` (see #36599 for context.)\nThis is by design, because plugin can require scratch buffers for processing or whatever and attaching lsp there would tank performances.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nThere should be a way to whitelist a buffer into the auto-attach logic, maybe something as simple as adding a buffer local variable like `b:lsp-autoattach = true`.\n\nImplementation would just add a `and` here: https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/c4ac36bfd9bc9826dde01839d10d0e65a7b3c9e2/runtime/lua/vim/lsp.lua#L475-L477",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "I think, if implemented, this should be an option given to commands that create a scratch buffer, not something you set after. Because:\n\n1. You can already have the desired behavior if you simulate a scratch buffer from a normal buffer while minding that `filetype` that triggers the check is set before `buftype`:\n\n```lua\nlocal function scratch()\n  -- create normal buffer\n  local buf = vim.api.nvim_create_buf(false, false)\n  -- set filetype which would trigger lsp\n  vim.bo[buf].filetype = \"json\"\n  -- simulate scratch buffer\n  vim.bo[buf].buftype = \"nofile\"\n  vim.bo[buf].bufhidden = \"hide\"\n  vim.bo[buf].swapfile = false\n  -- lsp is attached\n  vim.api.nvim_set_current_buf(buf)\nend\n```\n\n2. You won't have desired behavior on a scratch buffer with the new `lsp-autoattach` if you set it later than something that checks the condition:\n\n```lua\nlocal function scratch()\n  -- create scratch buffer\n  local buf = vim.api.nvim_create_buf(false, true)\n  -- set filetype which would trigger lsp\n  vim.bo[buf].filetype = \"json\"\n  -- set option too late :(\n  vim.bo[buf].lsp_autoattach = true\n  -- lsp is not attached\n  vim.api.nvim_set_current_buf(buf)\nend\n```\n\nSo instead it could be `vim.api.nvim_create_buf(<listed>, <scratch>, [<allow_lsp>])`. **However**, your suggestion about a separate option is good because it persists. Which means, if there is a plugin that lets you save scratch buffers between sessions, the LSP will attach on restore as well. So maybe we should have both.",
